    "title": "Coming of Age in Mississippi",
    "description": "The unforgettable memoir of a woman at the front lines of the civil rights movementâa harrowing account of black life in the rural South and a powerful affirmation of one personâs ability to affect change. âAnne Moodyâs autobiography is an eloquent, moving testimonial to her courage.ââChicago Tribune Born to a poor couple who were tenant farmers on a plantation in Mississippi, Anne Moody lived through some of the most dangerous days of the pre-civil rights era in the South. The week before she began high school came the news of Emmet Tillâs lynching. Before then, she had âknown the fear of hunger, hell, and the Devil. But now there was . . . the fear of being killed just because I was black.â In that moment was born the passion for freedom and justice that would change her life. A straight-A student who realized her dream of going to college when she won a basketball scholarship, she finally dared to join the NAACP in her junior year. Through the NAACP and later through CORE and SNCC, she experienced firsthand the demonstrations and sit-ins that were the mainstay of the civil rights movementâand the arrests and jailings, the shotguns, fire hoses, police dogs, billy clubs, and deadly force that were used to destroy it. A deeply personal story but also a portrait of a turning point in our nationâs destiny, this autobiography lets us see history in the making, through the eyes of one of the footsoldiers in the civil rights movement. Praise for Coming of Age in Mississippi âA history of our time, seen from the bottom up, through the eyes of someone who decided for herself that things had to be changed . . . a timely reminder that we cannot now relax.ââSenator Edward Kennedy, The New York Times Book Review âSomething is new here . . . rural southern black life begins to speak. It hits the page like a natural force, crude and undeniable and, against all principles of beauty, beautiful.ââThe Nation âEngrossing, sensitive, beautiful . . . so candid, so honest, and so touching, as to make it virtually impossible to put down.ââSan Francisco Sun-Reporter",
